description:
## Problem

When viewing a diff in diffstory where the last section is short and can't be scrolled to the top of the viewport, the section indicator in the status bar doesn't advance past the previous section.

Example: User presses 's' repeatedly to navigate to section 4/4, but the indicator stays at "section 3/4" because section 4's start position can't be placed at or before the viewport's YOffset.

## Root Cause

In `currentSection()` (story.go:556-563), the special case for "at bottom" only advances by ONE section:

```go
if m.viewport.AtBottom() && positionIdx < len(m.sectionPositions)-1 {
    nextSectionPos := m.sectionPositions[positionIdx+1]
    viewportBottom := currentLine + m.viewport.Height
    if nextSectionPos < viewportBottom {
        positionIdx++
        current = positionIdx + 1
    }
}
```

If sections 3 AND 4 both start within the viewport, it stops at 3.

## Fix

Change to loop through ALL remaining sections:

```go
if m.viewport.AtBottom() {
    viewportBottom := currentLine + m.viewport.Height
    for i := positionIdx + 1; i < len(m.sectionPositions); i++ {
        if m.sectionPositions[i] < viewportBottom {
            positionIdx = i
            current = i + 1
        } else {
            break
        }
    }
}
```

## Entrypoints

- `bubbletea/story.go` - `currentSection()` method

## Validation

- [ ] Section indicator advances to last visible section when at bottom
- [ ] make validate passes

## Problem
Current red/green color scheme is problematic for ~8% of men with deuteranopia/protanopia (red-green colorblindness). Added and deleted lines may be indistinguishable.

## Solution
Add a colorblind-friendly theme using blue/orange (or cyan/peach) which have:
- Very different perceived lightness
- Work across all common colorblindness types
- Blue is perceived similarly by almost everyone

## Implementation
```go
func ColorblindTheme() *Theme {
    return &Theme{
        styles: diffview.Styles{
            Added: diffview.ColorPair{
                Foreground: "#74c7ec", // Cyan/sky blue
            },
            Deleted: diffview.ColorPair{
                Foreground: "#fab387", // Orange/peach
            },
            Context: diffview.ColorPair{
                Foreground: "#6c7086", // Muted gray
            },
            HunkHeader: diffview.ColorPair{
                Foreground: "#cba6f7", // Mauve (distinct from both)
            },
            FileHeader: diffview.ColorPair{
                Foreground: "#f9e2af",
                Background: "#313244",
            },
        },
    }
}
```

## References
- https://davidmathlogic.com/colorblind/
- https://www.smashingmagazine.com/2024/02/designing-for-colorblindness/

## Entrypoints
- lipgloss/theme.go (add ColorblindTheme function)

## Validation
- [ ] ColorblindTheme() function exists and returns valid theme
- [ ] Colors are distinguishable in colorblind simulators
- [ ] Test with deuteranopia/protanopia simulation tools
- [ ] make validate passes

## Problem
Catppuccin-inspired pastel colors prioritize aesthetics over contrast. Some users need higher contrast for visibility, especially in bright environments or with visual impairments.

## Solution
Add a high-contrast theme with bold, saturated colors:
- Pure or near-pure hues
- Maximum lightness difference between elements
- Stark backgrounds for changed lines

## Implementation
```go
func HighContrastTheme() *Theme {
    return &Theme{
        styles: diffview.Styles{
            Added: diffview.ColorPair{
                Foreground: "#00ff00", // Pure green
            },
            Deleted: diffview.ColorPair{
                Foreground: "#ff4444", // Bright red
            },
            Context: diffview.ColorPair{
                Foreground: "#888888", // Medium gray (dim)
            },
            HunkHeader: diffview.ColorPair{
                Foreground: "#00ffff", // Cyan
            },
            FileHeader: diffview.ColorPair{
                Foreground: "#ffff00", // Yellow
                Background: "#333333",
            },
        },
    }
}
```

## Entrypoints
- lipgloss/theme.go (add HighContrastTheme function)

## Validation
- [ ] HighContrastTheme() function exists
- [ ] Colors are highly saturated and distinct
- [ ] Passes WCAG AAA contrast requirements
- [ ] make validate passes

## Problem
Chroma doesn't auto-detect terminal capabilities; must coordinate with Lipgloss.

## Implementation
Detect once and match both libraries:

```go
func getFormatterName() string {
    if ct := os.Getenv("COLORTERM"); ct == "truecolor" || ct == "24bit" {
        return "terminal16m"
    }
    if strings.Contains(os.Getenv("TERM"), "256") {
        return "terminal256"
    }
    return "terminal16"
}
```

Consider using lipgloss.CompleteColor for graceful degradation.

## Validation
- [ ] Works in true color terminal
- [ ] Degrades gracefully in 256-color terminal
- [ ] make validate passes

## Problem
Current ClassificationInput has single CommitInfo. Need to support PR-level with multiple commits.

## Changes
```go
// Before
type ClassificationInput struct {
    Commit CommitInfo
    Diff   Diff
}

// After
type ClassificationInput struct {
    Repo    string        `json:"repo"`
    Branch  string        `json:"branch"`
    Commits []CommitBrief `json:"commits"`
    Diff    Diff          `json:"diff"`
}

type CommitBrief struct {
    Hash    string `json:"hash"`
    Message string `json:"message"`
}
```

## Files
- classification.go

## Validation
- [ ] New types compile
- [ ] make validate passes

## Problem
Many developers are accustomed to GitHub's diff colors. Offering a familiar option reduces cognitive switching.

## Solution
Add a theme matching GitHub's diff color scheme:
- Added: green text on light green background
- Deleted: red text on light red/pink background
- Familiar to most developers

## Implementation
Extract colors from GitHub's CSS or use approximations:
```go
func GithubDarkTheme() *Theme {
    return &Theme{
        styles: diffview.Styles{
            Added: diffview.ColorPair{
                Foreground: "#3fb950", // GitHub green
                Background: "#1b4721", // Dark green bg
            },
            Deleted: diffview.ColorPair{
                Foreground: "#f85149", // GitHub red
                Background: "#5d1a1a", // Dark red bg
            },
            // ...
        },
    }
}
```

## Entrypoints
- lipgloss/theme.go

## Validation
- [ ] GithubDarkTheme() exists
- [ ] Colors reasonably match GitHub's diff view
- [ ] make validate passes
